1. cs.CL (Computation and Language) is the most likely category as the paper deals with natural language processing (NLP) and specifically focuses on dependency parsing of code-switching data. 
2. cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) is also likely as the paper proposes a neural stacking model for parsing code-switching data. 
3. cs.LG (Machine Learning) is another possible category as the paper uses machine learning techniques for parsing and normalization of code-switching data. 
4. cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) is a possible category as the paper proposes a neural model for parsing code-switching data. 
5. cs.SD (Sound) is a less likely category as the paper does not deal with sound or audio data, but it is still possible as code-switching can also occur in spoken language.
